But for aggregate functions (where an #RStats call is used on a set of results) far fewer calls would be required

There would still be some changeover point where for smaller data, you'd still be better off just materializing the data.frame representation and calculating on that

@mdsumner To actually answer your question: this would make it possible to process large data (stored in a SQLite DB) without having to materialize the actual data into a data.frame in #RStats e.g.

SELECT aggregate_func(x, y, z) FROM terabyte_db GROUP BY every_square_foot_on_earth;

This could mean that you could run arbitrary functions within the SQLite database without materializing tables into an #RStats data.frame.

But I see definite issues with speed - for scalar functions there would need to be a call back into R for each row. i.e. will be slow.

First proof-of-concept - user-defined-functions (UDFs) for SQLite written in #RStats

This is SQLite calling back into R to calculate a (scalar) result.
